  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Simultaneous settlement is the process of settling the sale of your current property and the purchase of your new property on the same day, often within hours of each other. It is the preferred arrangement for many upgraders and downsizers in Brisbane's inner east, because it avoids the need for bridging finance and removes the period of time you might otherwise spend without a home. In practice, it requires two separate transactions, two legal teams, two banks, and one day in which everything must go to plan. When it works, it is seamless. When one side runs into trouble, both transactions are at risk.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What simultaneous settlement actually involves</h2>
      <p>On the settlement date, your solicitor is managing two transactions simultaneously. In the morning, they receive the proceeds from your sale. Within the same day, those proceeds are applied to the purchase of your new property. In Queensland, settlements are now mostly conducted electronically through PEXA (Property Exchange Australia), which allows solicitors to manage both transactions in real time on a digital platform rather than exchanging physical documents and bank cheques.</p>

      <p>PEXA has made simultaneous settlements considerably more reliable than they were under the old paper-based system. Your solicitor can monitor the status of both transactions in real time, can flag delays as they emerge, and can coordinate with the other side electronically rather than waiting for phone calls to be returned. Most Queensland solicitors who handle residential conveyancing routinely manage simultaneous settlements through PEXA, and it is now the standard approach rather than the exception.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The domino risk: what happens when one side falls over</h2>
      <p>The most significant risk in a simultaneous settlement is that the two transactions are financially linked. Your purchase typically relies on the proceeds from your sale to fund the balance of the purchase price. If your sale falls over, your purchase may too. If your buyer's finance is declined on settlement day, or if they raise a dispute about the property condition that delays or prevents settlement, you can find yourself unable to complete your purchase without accessing alternative funds urgently.</p>

      <p>Similarly, if there is a problem on the purchase side, your sale may be affected. If your new property has an unresolved title issue or if your purchase contract requires adjustments that delay settlement, the timing of the whole chain shifts. Your buyer, who has their own moving plans for that day, is now dealing with a delay that came from your purchase rather than anything to do with them.</p>

      <p>This does not mean simultaneous settlements are dangerous or inadvisable. The vast majority complete without incident. But it does mean you should not attempt a simultaneous settlement with a buyer whose financial position is unclear, or with a purchase contract that has unresolved conditions or legal issues. Both transactions should be clean, unconditional, and well-managed before you set the settlement date.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How your solicitor coordinates the timing</h2>
      <p>Your solicitor will request that the settlement times be staggered, with your sale settling first and your purchase settling later in the same day. A typical structure in Queensland might have your sale settle at 10am, with the proceeds confirmed by 11am, and your purchase settling at 1 or 2pm using those funds. This sequencing means you are not waiting for sale proceeds that have not yet arrived before committing to the purchase settlement.</p>

      <p>In practice, your solicitor will be in contact with the vendor's solicitor on your purchase, coordinating the timing. Both transactions will be prepared in the PEXA workspace in advance, with all documents lodged and all figures confirmed, so that settlement on the day is a matter of electronic confirmation rather than last-minute preparation. The risk period is settlement day itself, and preparation in the weeks before is what determines how smooth that day is.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The bridging finance alternative</h2>
      <p>If you cannot align your sale and purchase settlements on the same day, or if you want to purchase before your sale completes, bridging finance is the alternative. A bridging loan covers the gap between your purchase settlement and your sale settlement, using your existing property as security. It lets you settle your purchase on the agreed date without waiting for your sale to complete.</p>

      <p>The cost of bridging finance depends on the loan size and the length of the bridging period, but it is not cheap. Interest on bridging loans typically runs at a higher rate than standard home loan rates, and you are paying interest on two properties simultaneously during the bridging period. If your sale takes longer than expected, those costs accumulate. Bridging finance is appropriate when the two settlement dates cannot be aligned and when the cost of carrying it is manageable given your financial position. It is not the right choice for sellers who are already stretching to fund the purchase.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The sell-first approach</h2>
      <p>The most conservative approach is to sell first, settle, and then purchase. This removes all risk of being caught without funds if the sale falls over, and it means you are in a strong unconditional position when you make an offer on your next property. The downside is that you may need to rent between settlement of your sale and settlement of your purchase, which adds cost and inconvenience. In a fast-moving market where properties are being purchased quickly, the period between selling and finding your next home can also be stressful, particularly if prices are rising.</p>

      <p>For sellers who are downsizing into a clearly defined price range with good stock available, selling first is often the lowest-risk path. For upgraders moving into a price range where suitable properties are rare and competition is strong, the risk of selling first and then not finding a suitable purchase quickly can outweigh the risk of attempting a simultaneous settlement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Building in buffer on your purchase settlement</h2>
      <p>One of the most practical things a seller attempting simultaneous settlement can do is negotiate a slightly longer settlement period on their purchase. If your sale is settling in 30 days, negotiating a 42 or 45 day settlement on your purchase gives you a buffer if the sale side needs extra time. It means the two settlement dates can still align, even if your sale hits a minor delay, without the purchase side being affected.</p>

      <p>Sellers sometimes resist requesting a longer settlement on their purchase because they worry the vendor will choose another buyer. In a competitive offer situation that concern is valid, and you need to weigh it against the logistical benefit of the buffer. But in many private treaty negotiations, a 10 to 14 day extension on settlement is a minor point that vendors and their agents will agree to without difficulty, particularly if everything else in your offer is strong.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to do if the timings do not align</h2>
      <p>If perfect alignment is not achievable, the options are bridging finance, a short-term rental between the two settlements, or negotiating extensions on one or both contracts. Most Queensland contracts allow for settlement extensions by mutual agreement, and in practice, when both parties understand the timing challenge, short extensions of a week or two are usually arranged without the transaction falling over. Your solicitor handles this, and it is a common scenario in any market where sellers are also buyers. The key is communicating the timing constraint clearly and early, so your solicitor has time to negotiate the extension before the original settlement date becomes urgent.</p>

